Place the @farro{1/2%cup} in a #medium pot{} with @water{2%cups} and a large pinch of @salt{pinch}. Bring to a boil, then reduce to a simmer. Cook ~{20-25%minutes}, until tender. Drain and return to the pot.

Wash and dry all produce. Meanwhile, core, seed, and dice the @roma tomato{1}(cored, seeded, and diced). Halve, peel, and mince 1/4 cup @shallot{1}(peeled and minced). Cut the @fresh mozzarella{4%oz} into small cubes.

Place your hand on top of one @chicken breasts{12%oz}, and slice into the middle of the meat (parallel to the #cutting board{}). Stop before cutting all the way through. Open the chicken up like a book. Repeat with the other chicken breast. Season on all sides with @herbes de Provence{1%tbsp}, @salt{to taste}, and @pepper{to taste}.

In a #small bowl{}, whisk together the shallots, @balsamic vinegar{2%tbsp}, @honey{1%unit}, and a large drizzle of @olive oil{1%tbsp} (to taste). Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a #large pan{} over high heat. Add the chicken. Cook ~{3-4%minutes} per side, until golden brown and cooked through. Remove from the pan and set aside.

Toss the salad: Toss the tomatoes, fresh mozzarella, and half the vinaigrette into the farro. Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}. Thinly slice the herby pan-seared chicken, and serve on a bed of farro salad. Drizzle the remaining vinaigrette over the top and enjoy!

> What do you get when you combine herbes de Provence with mozzarella and tomato? A French and Italian fusion… Fritalian! In all seriousness, we were shocked by how much we loved this flavor combination for lunch or dinner and have a feeling you will, too.